<subSubSection id="83966541FFC6FFCAFF06B243FA50B425" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="120" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" type="key">
<key id="BF1D61FBFFC6FFCAFF06B243FA50B425" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="120" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyStep id="70782E6FFFC6FFC9FF06B243FA50B27C" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B243FA50B25A" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" box="[151,1436,1336,1358]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B243FA50B25A" box="[151,1436,1336,1358]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">1. Apex of the forceps sharp and sclerotized................................................................. 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B22EFA50B27C" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" box="[151,1436,1365,1387]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B22EFA50B27C" box="[151,1436,1365,1387]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">- Apex of the forceps rounded........................................................................... 5</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="70782E6FFFC6FFC9FF06B209FA50B2B2" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B209FA50B290" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" box="[151,1436,1394,1416]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B209FA50B290" box="[151,1436,1394,1416]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">2(1). Forceps narrowing gradually toward the apex.............................................................. 3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B2EBFA50B2B2" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" box="[151,1436,1424,1446]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B2EBFA50B2B2" box="[151,1436,1424,1446]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">- Forceps sharpening abruptly at the apex................................................................... 4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="70782E6FFFC6FFC9FF06B2D6FA50B10C" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B2D6FA50B2F7" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B2D6FA50B2F7" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
3(2). Surface of the forceps without setae with 3 subapical denticles; lobes of the penis fused, without vestige of a dividing groove (
<bibRefCitation id="AF1D4B3BFFC6FFC9FF60B2B1FE44B2C8" author="Da-Silva, E. R." box="[241,392,1482,1504]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" pagination="413 - 416" refId="ref7115" refString="Da-Silva, E. R. (1993) Descricao do imago macho de Caenis cuniana Froehlich, com notas biologicas (Ephemeroptera, Caenidae). Revista Brasileira de Zoologia, 10 (3), 413 - 416. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0101 - 81751993000300007" type="journal article" year="1993">Da-Silva, 1993</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="53B72A4FFFC6FFC9FE01B2B1FE05B2F7" box="[400,457,1482,1504]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1491,1515]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1468]" captionTargetId="figure-27@5.[151,1436,181,1468]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Caenis marataoan sp. nov. female imago:A, habitus, dorsal view; B, habitus, lateral view; C, habitus, ventral view. (Scale: Figs 3A–C = 0.5 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521367/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
).................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="0C8C4D49FFC6FFC9FA97B2B0FA50B2F7" authorityName="Froechlich" authorityYear="1969" box="[1286,1436,1483,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Caenidae" genus="Caenis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuniana">
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC6FFC9FA97B2B0FA50B2F7" box="[1286,1436,1483,1504]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Caenis cuniana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B293FA50B10C" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B293FA50B10C" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
- Forceps generally with small tubercles and setae on outer basal margin; forceps 7.3–9.5 times longer than width at the middle; apophyses strongly developed, wide and long (
<bibRefCitation id="AF1D4B3BFFC6FFC9FD3DB17EFCBDB10D" author="Molineri, C. &amp; Grillet, M. E. &amp; Nieto, C. &amp; Dominguez, E. &amp; Guerrero, E." box="[684,881,1541,1563]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" pagination="39 - 50" refId="ref8240" refString="Molineri, C., Grillet, M. E., Nieto, C., Dominguez, E. &amp; Guerrero, E. (2011) New species and records for the mayfly families Caenidae, Leptohyphidae and Coryphoridae (Ephemeroptera, Pannota) from Venezuelan Guayana's uplands. Zootaxa, 2750 (1), 39 - 50. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2750.1.4" type="journal article" year="2011">
Molineri 
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC6FFC9FC99B17DFCFEB10D" box="[776,818,1541,1563]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">et al</emphasis>
. 2011
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="53B72A4FFFC6FFC9FCE8B17EFC7AB10D" box="[889,950,1541,1563]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[163,1419,196,1822]" captionTargetId="figure-19@4.[151,1436,181,1836]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Caenis marataoan sp. nov. male imago, genitalia: A, ventral view; B–E, variations in forceps. Abbreviations: f = forceps; p = penis; sp = styliger plate; a = apophysis; cs = central sclerite. (Scale: Fig. 2A = 0.1 mm; Figs 2B–E = 0.05 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521365" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521365/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Figs 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="53B72A4FFFC6FFC9FC50B17EFC02B10C" box="[961,974,1541,1563]" captionStart="FIGURE" captionStartId="6.[151,251,1838,1862]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1815]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[151,1436,181,1815]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE. 5. Caenis marataoan sp. nov. egg: A, general view; B, detail of micropyle; C, detail of polar cap. Abbreviations: pc = polar cap; c = chorion; mc = micropyle; sg = sperm guide. (Scale: Fig. 4A = 20 µm; Figs 4B, C = 10 µm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521369" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521369/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="53B72A4FFFC6FFC9FC48B17EFBDDB10C" box="[985,1041,1541,1563]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1978,2002]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,781,1955]" captionTargetId="figure-176@8.[151,1436,781,1955]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Male imagos, body dorsal view and genitalia ventral view: A–B, Brasilocaenis irmleri; C–D, B. elidioi; E–F, Caenis chamie; G–H, C. fittkaui. (Scale: Figs 5A, C, E, F = 1 mm; Figs 5B, D, F, H = 0.2 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521371/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">6A–F</figureCitation>
)................... 
<taxonomicName id="0C8C4D49FFC6FFC9FA85B17EFA50B10C" authorityName="Molineri, Grillet, Nieto, Dominguez &amp; Guerrero" authorityYear="2011" box="[1300,1436,1541,1563]" class="Insecta" family="Caenidae" genus="Caenis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="teipunensis">
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC6FFC9FA85B17EFA50B10C" box="[1300,1436,1541,1563]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">C. teipunensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="70782E6FFFC6FFC9FF06B159FA50B198" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B159FA51B142" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B159FA51B142" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
4(2). Forceps approximately six times longer than width at half length; about six setae present on ventral surface (
<bibRefCitation id="AF1D4B3BFFC6FFC9FB65B159FA56B12F" author="Malzacher, P." box="[1268,1434,1570,1592]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" pagination="83 - 103" refId="ref7911" refString="Malzacher, P. (1986) Caenidae aus dem Amazonasgebiet (Insecta, Ephemeroptera). Spixiana, 9, 83 - 103." type="journal article" year="1986">Malzacher, 1986</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="53B72A4FFFC6FFC9FF7BB13BFE98B142" box="[234,340,1599,1622]" captionStart="FIGURE" captionStartId="6.[151,251,1838,1862]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1815]" captionTargetId="figure-19@6.[151,1436,181,1815]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE. 5. Caenis marataoan sp. nov. egg: A, general view; B, detail of micropyle; C, detail of polar cap. Abbreviations: pc = polar cap; c = chorion; mc = micropyle; sg = sperm guide. (Scale: Fig. 4A = 20 µm; Figs 4B, C = 10 µm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521369" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521369/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Figs 5B, C</figureCitation>
, 11)............................................................................ 
<taxonomicName id="0C8C4D49FFC6FFC9FAB3B13BFA51B142" authorityName="Malzacher" authorityYear="1986" box="[1314,1437,1600,1621]" class="Insecta" family="Caenidae" genus="Caenis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="candelata">
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC6FFC9FAB3B13BFA51B142" box="[1314,1437,1600,1621]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">C. candelata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B126FA50B198" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B126FA50B198" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
- Forceps approximately 9-11 times longer than width at half length, approximately 15-20 setae present on ventral surface (
<bibRefCitation id="AF1D4B3BFFC6FFC9FF60B101FE5BB187" author="Malzacher, P." box="[241,407,1658,1680]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" pagination="83 - 103" refId="ref7911" refString="Malzacher, P. (1986) Caenidae aus dem Amazonasgebiet (Insecta, Ephemeroptera). Spixiana, 9, 83 - 103." type="journal article" year="1986">Malzacher, 1986</bibRefCitation>
: 
