, 10).................................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="0C8C4D49FFC6FFC9FAADB100FA50B198" authorityName="Malzacher" authorityYear="1986" box="[1340,1436,1658,1680]" class="Insecta" family="Caenidae" genus="Caenis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fittkaui">
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC6FFC9FAADB100FA50B198" box="[1340,1436,1658,1680]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">C. fittkaui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="70782E6FFFC6FFC9FF06B1ECFA50B012" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B1ECFA50B1DC" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B1ECFA50B1DC" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">5(1). Finger-like median process present in abdominal tergum II; fore leg twice as long as hind leg or longer; forceps and sclerites of the genitalia strongly colored........................................................................... 6</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B1A8FA50B012" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B1A8FA50B012" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">- Abdominal tergum II without median projections (but lateral projections may be present); fore leg at most 1.8 times the length of hind leg; forceps and sclerites of the genitalia nearly uncolored)............................................. 7</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="70782E6FFFC6FFC9FF06B076FA51B06C" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B076FA51B028" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B076FA51B028" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
6(5). Lateral filaments of abdominal segments relatively short; lobes of penis short and laterally rounded; apophyses of the styliger sclerite long and thin, somewhat distanced from the base of the forceps (
<bibRefCitation id="AF1D4B3BFFC6FFC9FC30B051FB8BB028" author="Malzacher, P." box="[929,1095,1834,1856]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" pagination="1 - 20" refId="ref8068" refString="Malzacher, P. (2001) South and Central American Caenis species with rounded forceps tips (Insecta: Ephemeroptera: Caenidae). Stuttgarter Beitrage zur Naturkunde, 626, 1 - 20. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 01650424.2012.713112" type="journal article" year="2001">Malzacher, 2001</bibRefCitation>
: Figs 7A–E)...... 
<taxonomicName id="0C8C4D49FFC6FFC9FA8BB050FA51B028" authorityName="Malzacher" authorityYear="2001" box="[1306,1437,1834,1856]" class="Insecta" family="Caenidae" genus="Caenis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plaumanni">
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC6FFC9FA8BB050FA51B028" box="[1306,1437,1834,1856]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">C. plaumanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B033FA51B06C" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B033FA51B06C" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
- Central sclerite of styliger elongated; apophyses of styliger sclerite broad and short; penis whitish with rounded lateral lobes (
<bibRefCitation id="AF1D4B3BFFC6FFC9FF60B01EFDC5B06D" author="Molineri, C. &amp; Malzacher, P." box="[241,521,1893,1915]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" pagination="1 - 31" refId="ref8189" refString="Molineri, C. &amp; Malzacher, P. (2007) South American Caenis Stephens (Ephemeroptera, Caenidae), new species and stage descriptions. Zootaxa, 1660 (1), 1 - 31. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1660.1.1" type="journal article" year="2007">Molineri &amp; Malzacher, 2007</bibRefCitation>
: Figs 96–98).......................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="0C8C4D49FFC6FFC9FADBB01EFA51B06C" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Malzacher" authorityYear="2007" box="[1354,1437,1893,1915]" class="Insecta" family="Caenidae" genus="Caenis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uruzu">
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC6FFC9FADBB01EFA51B06C" box="[1354,1437,1893,1915]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">C. uruzu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="70782E6FFFC6FFC9FF06B0F9FA50B0A2" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B0F9FA50B080" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" box="[151,1436,1922,1944]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B0F9FA50B080" box="[151,1436,1922,1944]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">7(5). Lobes of the penis totally fused, without a median groove.................................................... 8</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B0DBFA50B0A2" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" box="[151,1436,1952,1974]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B0DBFA50B0A2" box="[151,1436,1952,1974]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">- Groove separating the lobes of the penis visible............................................................ 9</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="70782E6FFFC6FFCAFF06B0C6FA50B7DD" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="120" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC6FFC9FF06B0C6FA50B0E7" blockId="9.[151,1437,1336,2032]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC6FFC9FF06B0C6FA50B0E7" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
8(7). Forceps somewhat curved toward median line; without trichomes or minute spines at apex; posterior margin of styliger plate more or less straight; penis rounded and narrow at the base (
<bibRefCitation id="AF1D4B3BFFC6FFC9FCBDB0A1FBEAB0F8" author="Pereira, S. M. &amp; Da-Silva, E. R." box="[812,1062,2010,2032]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" pagination="1 - 8" refId="ref8576" refString="Pereira, S. M. &amp; Da-Silva, E. R. (1990) Nova especie de Caenis Stephens, 1835 do sudeste do Brasil (Ephemeroptera, Caenidae). Boletim do Museu Nacional (Rio de Janeiro), Zoologia, 341, 1 - 8." type="journal article" year="1990">Pereira &amp; Da-Silva, 1990</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="53B72A4FFFC6FFC9FBBFB0A1FBABB0E7" box="[1070,1127,2010,2032]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1840]" captionTargetId="figure-27@3.[151,1436,181,1840]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Caenis marataoan sp. nov. male imago: A, habitus, dorsal view; B, habitus, lateral view; C, habitus, ventral view; D, detail of thorax (ventral view); E, detail of abdomen (dorsal view). (Scale: Figs 1A–E = 0.5 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521363" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521363/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
)................ 
<taxonomicName id="0C8C4D49FFC6FFC9FAAEB0A0FA50B0E7" authorityName="Pereira &amp; Da-Silva" authorityYear="1990" box="[1343,1436,2011,2032]" class="Insecta" family="Caenidae" genus="Caenis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cigana">
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC6FFC9FAAEB0A0FA50B0E7" box="[1343,1436,2011,2032]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">C. cigana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC5FFCAFF06B7E3FA50B7DD" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,819]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC5FFCAFF06B7E3FA50B7DD" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
- Forceps curved toward median line, covered with trichomes with 2–3 minute spines at apex; posterior margin of styliger plate short convex; penis square-shaped, not narrow at base.................................. 
<taxonomicName id="0C8C4D49FFC5FFCAFB09B7CEFA85B7DD" authority="Nascimento &amp; Rodrigues &amp; Ale-Rocha &amp; Lima, 2022" authorityName="Nascimento &amp; Rodrigues &amp; Ale-Rocha &amp; Lima" authorityYear="2022" box="[1176,1353,181,202]" class="Insecta" family="Caenidae" genus="Caenis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marataoan" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC5FFCAFB09B7CEFA85B7DD" box="[1176,1353,181,202]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">Caenis marataoan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC5FFCAFAC1B7CEFA50B7DD" bold="true" box="[1360,1436,181,202]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="E2CB57A3FFC5FFCAFAC1B7CEFA50B7DD" box="[1360,1436,181,202]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="70782E6FFFC5FFCAFF06B7A9FA50B612" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC5FFCAFF06B7A9FA50B7F0" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,819]" box="[151,1436,210,232]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC5FFCAFF06B7A9FA50B7F0" box="[151,1436,210,232]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">9(7). Penis with laterally protruding lobes.................................................................... 10</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC5FFCAFF06B78BFA50B612" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,819]" box="[151,1436,239,261]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC5FFCAFF06B78BFA50B612" box="[151,1436,239,261]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">- Lobes of penis very short and not or only slightl y protruding................................................ 13</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="70782E6FFFC5FFCAFF06B676FA50B628" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC5FFCAFF06B676FA50B635" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,819]" box="[151,1436,269,291]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC5FFCAFF06B676FA50B635" box="[151,1436,269,291]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">10(9). Posterior margin of styliger plate straight or rounded....................................................... 11</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC5FFCAFF06B650FA50B628" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,819]" box="[151,1436,298,320]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC5FFCAFF06B650FA50B628" box="[151,1436,298,320]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">- Posterior margin of styliger plate subtriangular............................................................ 12</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="70782E6FFFC5FFCAFF06B633FA51B6A3" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC5FFCAFF06B633FA50B66D" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,819]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC5FFCAFF06B633FA50B66D" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
11(10). Fore margin of the styliger sclerite convex; apophyses of styliger sclerite bent inwards (
<bibRefCitation id="AF1D4B3BFFC5FFCAFBA5B63CFB15B64A" author="Malzacher, P." box="[1076,1241,327,349]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120" pagination="1 - 20" refId="ref8068" refString="Malzacher, P. (2001) South and Central American Caenis species with rounded forceps tips (Insecta: Ephemeroptera: Caenidae). Stuttgarter Beitrage zur Naturkunde, 626, 1 - 20. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 01650424.2012.713112" type="journal article" year="2001">Malzacher, 2001</bibRefCitation>
: Figs 9A–I).................................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="0C8C4D49FFC5FFCAFAAEB61EFA50B66D" baseAuthorityName="Navas" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[1343,1436,357,378]" class="Insecta" family="Caenidae" genus="Caenis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenella">
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC5FFCAFAAEB61EFA50B66D" box="[1343,1436,357,378]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">C. tenella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC5FFCAFF06B6F8FA51B6A3" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,819]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC5FFCAFF06B6F8FA51B6A3" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
- Fore margin of the styliger sclerite straight; apophyses of styliger sclerite pointed and straight (
<bibRefCitation id="AF1D4B3BFFC5FFCAFB1DB6F9FAF3B68F" author="Lima, L. R. C. &amp; Molineri, C. &amp; Pinheiro, U." box="[1164,1343,386,408]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120" pagination="589 - 592" refId="ref7511" refString="Lima, L. R. C., Molineri, C. &amp; Pinheiro, U. (2015 b) A new species of Caenis Stephens, 1836 (Ephemeroptera: Caenidae) from Southern Brazil. Zootaxa, 3941 (4), 589 - 592. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3941.4.8" type="journal article" year="2015">
Lima 
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC5FFCAFB56B6F8FB3FB680" box="[1223,1267,386,408]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">et al</emphasis>
. 2015b
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="53B72A4FFFC5FFCAFADBB6F9FF30B6A2" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1200,1224]" captionTargetBox="[160,1432,279,1175]" captionTargetId="figure-69@1.[151,1436,273,1176]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distributional map with records of Brasilocaenis irmleri, B. elidioi, Caenis chamie, C. fittkaui, and Caenis marataoan sp. nov. A, Map of South America indicating previous records; B, Map of Piauí State, Brazil with new distributional records." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521361" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521361/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">Figs 1C, D</figureCitation>
)........................................................................................ 
<taxonomicName id="0C8C4D49FFC5FFCAFAABB6DBFA51B6A3" box="[1338,1437,415,437]" class="Insecta" family="Caenidae" genus="Caenis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gaucha">
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC5FFCAFAABB6DBFA51B6A3" box="[1338,1437,415,437]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">C. gaucha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="70782E6FFFC5FFCAFF06B6C6FA50B53D" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC5FFCAFF06B6C6FA50B6F8" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,819]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC5FFCAFF06B6C6FA50B6F8" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
12(10). Apical margin of penis convex; apophyses of the styliger sclerite bent inwardly, fore margin of the styliger sclerite concave (
<bibRefCitation id="AF1D4B3BFFC5FFCAFF60B6A1FE5BB6F8" author="Malzacher, P." box="[241,407,474,496]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120" pagination="31 - 39" refId="ref7979" refString="Malzacher, P. (1990) Neue Arten der Eintagsfliegen-Familie Caenidae (Insecta, Ephemeroptera) aus Sudamerika. Studies on Neotropical Fauna and Environment, 25, 31 - 39. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 01650529009360799" type="journal article" year="1990">Malzacher, 1990</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="53B72A4FFFC5FFCAFE0EB6A1FDC5B6E7" box="[415,521,474,496]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1200,1224]" captionTargetBox="[160,1432,279,1175]" captionTargetId="figure-69@1.[151,1436,273,1176]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distributional map with records of Brasilocaenis irmleri, B. elidioi, Caenis chamie, C. fittkaui, and Caenis marataoan sp. nov. A, Map of South America indicating previous records; B, Map of Piauí State, Brazil with new distributional records." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521361" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521361/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">Figs 1A, B</figureCitation>
)............................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="0C8C4D49FFC5FFCAFA81B6A1FA50B6F8" authorityName="Malzacher" authorityYear="1990" box="[1296,1436,474,495]" class="Insecta" family="Caenidae" genus="Caenis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pflugfelderi">
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC5FFCAFA81B6A1FA50B6F8" box="[1296,1436,474,495]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">C. pflugfelderi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC5FFCAFF06B683FA50B53D" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,819]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC5FFCAFF06B683FA50B53D" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
- Apical margin of penis straight; apophyses of the styliger sclerite pointed and straight, fore margin of the styliger sclerite straight (
<bibRefCitation id="AF1D4B3BFFC5FFCAFEAEB56EFD47B53D" author="Alba-Tercedor, J. &amp; Mosquera, S." box="[319,651,533,555]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120" pagination="61 - 67" refId="ref6918" refString="Alba-Tercedor, J. &amp; Mosquera, S. (1999) Caenis chamie, a new species from Colombia (Ephemeroptera: Caenidae). Pan- Pacific Entomologist, 75 (2), 61 - 67." type="journal article" year="1999">Alba-Tercedor &amp; Mosquera, 1999</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation id="53B72A4FFFC5FFCAFD02B56EFD03B53D" box="[659,719,533,555]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1200,1224]" captionTargetBox="[160,1432,279,1175]" captionTargetId="figure-69@1.[151,1436,273,1176]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distributional map with records of Brasilocaenis irmleri, B. elidioi, Caenis chamie, C. fittkaui, and Caenis marataoan sp. nov. A, Map of South America indicating previous records; B, Map of Piauí State, Brazil with new distributional records." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521361" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521361/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">Figs 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="53B72A4FFFC5FFCAFD4AB56EFD24B53C" box="[731,744,533,555]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1491,1515]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1468]" captionTargetId="figure-27@5.[151,1436,181,1468]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Caenis marataoan sp. nov. female imago:A, habitus, dorsal view; B, habitus, lateral view; C, habitus, ventral view. (Scale: Figs 3A–C = 0.5 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521367/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">4</figureCitation>
)............................................... 
<taxonomicName id="0C8C4D49FFC5FFCAFAAAB56EFA50B53D" authorityName="Alba-Tercedor &amp; Mosquera" authorityYear="1999" box="[1339,1436,533,554]" class="Insecta" family="Caenidae" genus="Caenis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chamie">
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC5FFCAFAAAB56EFA50B53D" box="[1339,1436,533,554]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">C. chamie</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="70782E6FFFC5FFCAFF06B549FA50B588" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC5FFCAFF06B549FA51B573" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,819]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC5FFCAFF06B549FA51B573" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
13(9). Lobes of the penis very short and swollen at base; styliger plate usually covering the penis; prosternal triangle narrow and triangular, usually closed toward apex (
<bibRefCitation id="AF1D4B3BFFC5FFCAFDF5B534FCC6B572" author="Malzacher, P." box="[612,778,591,613]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120" pagination="83 - 103" refId="ref7911" refString="Malzacher, P. (1986) Caenidae aus dem Amazonasgebiet (Insecta, Ephemeroptera). Spixiana, 9, 83 - 103." type="journal article" year="1986">Malzacher, 1986</bibRefCitation>
: Figs 13A, 16, 18A, B).......................... 
<taxonomicName id="0C8C4D49FFC5FFCAFAA3B52BFA51B573" authorityName="Malzacher" authorityYear="1985" box="[1330,1437,591,613]" class="Insecta" family="Caenidae" genus="Caenis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sigillata">
<emphasis id="F9F8EAD8FFC5FFCAFAA3B52BFA51B573" box="[1330,1437,591,613]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">C. sigillata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB3336CAFFC5FFCAFF06B516FA50B588" blockId="10.[151,1437,151,819]" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">
<keyLead id="707D95FFFFC5FFCAFF06B516FA50B588" pageId="10" pageNumber="120">- Lobes of the penis relatively long; styliger plate not covering penis; prosternal triangle broad and usually open toward apex .................................................................................................. 14</keyLead>
